    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "56a1824f_f7811fcc",
        "filename": "buildbucket/proto/config/project_config.proto",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 173,
      "author": {
        "id": 1001907
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-03-25T18:19:22Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "note that we currently have no way to enforce this :(.\n\nI think eventually we should have a butler command \u0027namespace\u0027 which will return a new value of LOGDOG_STREAM_SERVER_PATH. This new value will be served by the same butler instance, but stream (or namespace) creation requests will automatically apply the namespace.\n\nTo that end, the generation of the \u0027log url\u0027 should also be an rpc to butler.\n\nIf we do both of these, then the ONLY envvar needed is $LOGDOG_STREAM_SERVER_PATH, at which point we can change it to `LUCI_CONTEXT[\u0027logdog\u0027][\u0027butler\u0027]`",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 173,
        "startChar": 22,
        "endLine": 173,
        "endChar": 65
      },
      "revId": "3bb601b32b06d0abcc7e3445c56e1ea44c75c898",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "dc9417e1_aaa80e1e",
        "filename": "buildbucket/proto/config/project_config.proto",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 173,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-03-25T18:41:14Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "yes, my thoughts exactly. I agree that only $LOGDOG_STREAM_SERVER_PATH would be better. It also contributes to omitting other LOGDOG_* vars.\n\nHow hard/easy it is to start a new local butler server connected to another butler server? I think essentially this is the butler proxy that we talked about before.",
      "parentUuid": "56a1824f_f7811fcc",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 173,
        "startChar": 22,
        "endLine": 173,
        "endChar": 65
      },
      "revId": "3bb601b32b06d0abcc7e3445c56e1ea44c75c898",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "91abff9d_db94f593",
        "filename": "buildbucket/proto/config/project_config.proto",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 173,
      "author": {
        "id": 1001907
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-03-25T20:12:46Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think this could be accomplished by doing \n\n    open(stream_server_path, \u0027rwb\u0027) as fd\n    fd.write(\u0027{\"command\": \"new_namespace\", \"namespace\": \"foo/bar\"}\u0027)\n    new_stream_server_path \u003d fd.read()\n\nThe protocol is already that you open the stream_server_path and write a JSON blob to it (to describe the rest of the data you plan to write). I think this could be trivially extended to accepting commands (in the form above), and allowing the connected socket to be bidirectional.\n\nThe server would read the command, then:\n  * make a new named pipe/unix socket/whatever\n  * add that to the list of things the butler loop is listening to\n  * write the name of that new thing back to the connection\n\n\nSo, ultimately, there would still only be one butler process running.\n\nThis could also be used to move out the url stuff:\n\n    open(stream_server_path, \u0027rwb\u0027) as fd\n    fd.write(\u0027{\"command\": \"get_log_url\", \"stream_name\": \"foo/bar\"}\u0027)\n    http_url_for_foo_bar \u003d fd.read()",
      "parentUuid": "dc9417e1_aaa80e1e",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 173,
        "startChar": 22,
        "endLine": 173,
        "endChar": 65
      },
      "revId": "3bb601b32b06d0abcc7e3445c56e1ea44c75c898",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "25ee47f1_3be16f85",
        "filename": "buildbucket/proto/config/project_config.proto",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 173,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-03-25T23:22:45Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "i thought about this a bit and not sure now. Without $LOGDOG_NAMESPACE, a sub-recipe wouldn\u0027t know what to put in $build.proto step log, or what it will put will be relative to its proxy, as opposed to what butler that kitchen manages. WDYT?\n\nat the same time, this seems to be mostly sub-recipe thing. I don\u0027t see why kitchen needs this param. I am tempted to simply remove $LOGDOG_NAMESPACE from this protocol and ask the user executable to always write \"u/build.proto\". If it needs to rub sub-recipes, then it can manage $LOGDOG_NAMESPACE on its own. Kitchen does not need to know about this.",
      "parentUuid": "91abff9d_db94f593",
      "range": {
